With the increase of human life expectancy, more and more people, especially the elderly, are suffering from neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson’ s, Alzheimer’ s and senile dementia (
Khan et al., 2019
; 
Si et al., 2021
). At present, several chemosynthetic drugs with various side effects are mainly used for the treatment of cognitive deficits and memory loss related to these diseases (
Sabaragamuwa et al., 2018
). Also, 

Ginkgo biloba

L., folium extract as a natural medicine was confirmed to be effective and safe in treating mild cognitive impairment and Alzheimer’ s disease and had been approved by European Medicines Agency (
Yang et al., 2016
). Thus, searching for alternatives from natural resources with better neuroprotective activities and less adverse effects is a promising direction. As a continuous study of our research team and collaborators to screen undescribed neuroprotective candidates from natural plants (
Luo et al., 2020
; 
Wu et al., 2020
), we found the 70% ethanol extracts of the flowers of 

R. hugonis

exhibited moderate neuroprotective activity (
Table S1
). However, to the best of our knowledge, detailed phytochemical investigations on this species have not been

